Bayesian regression project

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(BAS)
library(GGally)

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The database consists of 651 observations of 32 variables. Each observation represents a movie randomly sampled among those who have been released in theatres between 1972 and 2014. It is necessary to discuss the range of application of the results obtained using this database in terms of generalizability and causality.

  • Generalizability to movies outside of this database is possible thanks to the practice of random sampling.

  • It is not possible to establish a link of causality between different variables because random assignment was not used.

Part 2: Data manipulation

Many of the variables contained in the initial database can not be considered explanatory with respect to audience_score. For this reason, we are going to work with the following subset of variables.

movies <- dplyr::select(movies, audience_score, title_type, genre, mpaa_rating, thtr_rel_month, runtime, thtr_rel_year, imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_score, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, top200_box)

Then, we will create five new categorical variables. The first is feature_film with levels yes (movies that are feature films) and no.

movies <- mutate(movies, feature_film = as.factor(ifelse(title_type == 'Feature Film', "yes", "no")))

The second is drama with levels yes (movies that are dramas) and no.

movies <- mutate(movies, drama = as.factor(ifelse(genre == 'Drama', "yes", "no")))

The third is mpaa_rating_R with levels yes (movies that are meant for restricted audiences) and no.

movies <- mutate(movies, mpaa_rating_R = as.factor(ifelse(mpaa_rating == 'R', "yes", "no")))

The fourth is oscar_season with levels yes (if movie is released in October, November or December) and no.

movies <- mutate(movies, oscar_season = as.factor(ifelse((thtr_rel_month >= 10) & (thtr_rel_month <= 12), "yes", "no")))

The fifth and final is summer_season with levels yes (if movie is released in May, June, July, or August) and no.

movies <- mutate(movies, summer_season = as.factor(ifelse((thtr_rel_month >= 5) & (thtr_rel_month <= 8), "yes", "no")))

The variables title_type, genre, mpaa_rating and thtr_rel_month can be dropped from the reduced database.

movies <- dplyr::select(movies, audience_score, feature_film, drama, mpaa_rating_R, oscar_season, summer_season, runtime, thtr_rel_year, imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_score, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, top200_box)

The variable of interest is audience_score, whereas all the other variables are potential explanatory variables. It is interesting to plot the distribution of audience_score with a histogram.

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = audience_score)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) + labs(x = 'Audience Score', y = 'Count')

It appears that audience_score has a bimodal left-skewed distribution, with two peaks around 50% and 80%, respectively. There are relatively few movies that the public utterly dislikes. Does this mean that people are more willing to rate a movie on Rotten Tomatoes when they liked it? This may be a source of bias in the results.

The relationship between audience_score and the new variables defined in the previous section can be investigated by calculating summary statistics and using box plots. The following box plots will show also the mean of the distribution with a rhomb symbol.

The box plots show that, except for a couple of outliers, non-feature films tend to have a much higher audience_score than feature films. This is then a good candidate explanatory variable.

The R-rating does not seem to have a major correlation with the audience_score, except for the fact that the upper limit of the first quantile of R-rated movies is slightly lower than that of non R-rated movies.

It can be noticed that summer_season and oscar_season are mutually exclusive variables. For this reason, the distribution of audience_score of movies released either in the summer season, or in the Oscar season or during the rest of the year can be studied at the same time. For this purpose, we will define a new variable called season with levels Summer, Oscar or Other.

new_movies <- transmute(movies, season = as.factor(ifelse(summer_season == 'yes', 'Summer', ifelse(oscar_season == 'yes', 'Oscar' ,"Other"))))

new_movies['audience_score'] <- movies$audience_score

The season in which the movie is released does not appear to be highly correlated with its audience score, except for the fact that the distribution of audience_score of movies released in the Oscar season is more left skewed. Could this be due to the fact that studios tend to release their better movies during the Oscar season?

Finally, we can use the ggpairs function to visualize the scatter plots of each pair of numerical variables in the database, the distribution of the single variables, and the correlation coefficient of each pair.

ggpairs(na.omit(movies), columns = c(1,7,8,9,10,11))

The audience_score is most noticeably collinear with the imdb_rating and the critics_score variables. The first case is not surprising, since audience_score and imdb_rating represent the same thing on two different web sites and with two different scales. The second result is perhaps more interesting, because it shows that the tastes of the public and of the critics are somewhat aligned.

Part 4: Modeling

Model training

Given that there are \(16\) candidate explanatory variables, there are \(2^{16} = 65536\) possible linear models of the audience_score. The space of possible models will be explored by means of the bas.lm function - Bayesian Adaptive Sampling (BAS) for Bayesian Model Averaging and Variable Selection in Linear Models - available in the BAS package. In the following application of the bas.lm algorithm, each model has a uniform prior probability equal to \(1/2^{16}\). This is therefore a non-informative prior, which is used as a starting point in absence of more detailed information. The prior distribution for regression coefficients corresponds to the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC), which includes a penalty function depending on the number of regression parameters.

# Filter out the lines containing one or more NA value
movies_no_na <- na.omit(movies)

# Fit the model using Bayesian linear regression, `bas.lm` function in the `BAS` package
bma_audience <- bas.lm(audience_score ~ . , data = movies_no_na,
                   prior = "BIC", 
                   modelprior = uniform())

The application of the summary function to the results of the Bayesian regression outputs a table containing a wealth of useful information. The first column corresponds to the posterior inclusion probability of each model coefficient given the training data set. The following columns correspond to the first five linear regression models with highest posterior probability (PostProbs) in descending order. The zeros and ones indicate if a variable is present in the model or not. Other values tabulated for each model are the Bayes factor (BF) of the model with respect to the Highest Probability Model (HPM), the R-squared (R2) in the ordinary least squares sense, the number of variables (dim) and the log of marginal likelihood (logmarg).

It can be seen that the top two models have posterior probability around \(13\%\), which is much larger than the initial uniform prior. Also, none of the models has more than five parameters, including the intercept. These five models account for approximately \(75\%\) of the variation of the dependent variable. The HPM contains the following variables:

  • runtime

  • imdb_rating

  • critics_score.

It can also be noticed that the logmarg of the HPM has the lowest absolute value because it is approximately equal to \(-\frac{1}{2}\)BIC and the algorithm seeks to minimize the value of BIC.

Model diagnostics

The posterior inclusion probabilities (PIP) of each explanatory variable are plotted below. The values above \(50\%\) are highlighted in blue.

par(mar=c(8,4,2,2))  
plot(bma_audience, which = 4, ask = F, caption = "", sub.caption = "", col.in = "blue", col.ex = "darkgrey", lwd = 3)

It can be noticed in the previous plot that the only variables with PIP higher than \(50\%\) are those included in the HPM.

Model uncertainty can also be visualized in the following way. The y-axis contains all the predictors and the intercept, whereas the x-axis represents to the logarithm of the posterior odds of each model (having used a uniform model prior, this corresponds to the logarithm of the Bayes factor). The columns correspond to the 17 models with higher posterior probability. The cells colored in black indicate that the corresponding predictor is not included in the model.

image(bma_audience, rotate = FALSE)

It can be seen that the BAS algorithm is very efficient in producing parsimonious linear models thanks to the BIC prior.

Five new variables have been created in the previous section. The posterior distribution of their respective coefficients is plotted below. Vertical lines represent the probabilty that each coefficient is equal to zero.

coef_audience <- coefficients(bma_audience)

# plot posterior uncertainty in coefficients
par(mfrow = c(3,2))
plot(coef_audience, subset = 2:6, ask = FALSE)

As can be seen, all the newly created variables have coefficients that have at least \(60\%\) probability to be equal to zero.

Another useful diagnostic test is to plot the distribution of residuals versus the predictions under the Bayesian Model Average (BMA) in order to verify that the residuals are randomly scattered with zero mean.

plot(bma_audience, which = 1, add.smooth = F,
ask = F, pch = 16, sub.caption="", caption="")
abline(a = 0, b = 0, col = "darkgrey", lwd = 2)

The previous plot presents a typical fan shape which contradicts the hypothesis of random residuals. The predictions are more accurate for higher values of audience_score. This is due to the fact that, in this database, higher values of audience_score are much more frequent than the lower.

Part 5: Prediction

The predicting capabilities of the Bayesian regression model are tested on the 2016 movie Jane Got a Gun. The values for all the predictors can be found under the following links:

  • Rotten Tomatoes

  • Imdb

  • Wikipedia.

A new data frame is then created.

newmovie <- data.frame(feature_film = "yes",
                       drama = "yes",
                       mpaa_rating_R = "yes",
                       runtime = 98, 
                       thtr_rel_year = 2016,
                       oscar_season = "no",
                       summer_season = "no",
                       imdb_rating = 5.9, 
                       imdb_num_votes = 19806,
                       critics_score = 43,
                       best_pic_nom = "no", 
                       best_pic_win = "no",
                       best_actor_win = "no",
                       best_actress_win = "yes",
                       best_dir_win = "no",
                       top200_box = "no")

The audience_score of this movie will be predicted using the four most significant models produced by the BAS algorithm. Along with the predicted values, \(95\%\) credible intervals will be calculated. We begin with the BMA, which is obtained by averaging all models using their posterior probabilities. This is the best prediction under the squared error loss function.

BMA.new = predict(bma_audience, newdata = newmovie, se.fit = TRUE, estimator = "BMA")
confint(BMA.new, parm = "pred")
##          2.5%    97.5%     pred
## [1,] 33.36289 73.24507 52.27368
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

Then, we can apply the Best Predictive Model (BPM), which is the single model the predictions of which are closest to those of the BMA.

BPM.new = predict(bma_audience, newdata = newmovie, se.fit = TRUE, estimator = "BPM")
confint(BPM.new, parm = "pred")
##          2.5%    97.5%     pred
## [1,] 32.37735 72.17001 52.27368
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

Another option is to use the Median Probability Model (MPM), which includes all predictors whose marginal posterior inclusion probabilities are greater than 0.5.

MPM.new = predict(bma_audience, newdata = newmovie, se.fit = TRUE, estimator = "MPM")
confint(MPM.new, parm = "pred")
##       2.5%    97.5%     pred
## [1,] 32.78 72.41878 52.59939
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

Finally, we can use the Highest Probability Model (HPM).

HPM.new = predict(bma_audience, newdata = newmovie, se.fit = TRUE, estimator = "HPM")
confint(HPM.new, parm = "pred")
##          2.5%    97.5%     pred
## [1,] 33.13699 72.61171 52.87435
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

The difference both in terms of predicted value and in terms of credible interval among the four models is negligible for practical purposes. The real value of the audience_score of Jane Got a Gun is \(37\%\). This value is noticeably lower than the \(52\%\) predicted by all four models, but it is contained in all the corresponding credible intervals.

Part 6: Conclusion

This exercise has highlighted the main steps in the construction of a Bayesian regression model, beginning with tidying the data and creating new variables, following with EDA, model generation, diagnostics and final application. Only a small subset of the variables present in the database turn out to be meaningful predictors of the audience_score. Furthermore, the distribution of audience_score in the database is significantly left-skewed, leading to more accurate predictions for higher values of this variable. The selected test case, on the contrary, has relatively low audience_score, leading to a poor accuracy of the prediction. It would be interesting to re-train a Bayesian regression model on a database in which the audience_score is more uniformly distributed.
